During the {{ill|Satsuma Rebellion|ja|西南戦争|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Satsuma Rebellion|qq=}}, dissatisfied samurai from the former Nakatsu Domain formed the {{ill|Nakatsu Corps|ja|中津隊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakatsu Corps|qq=}} and burned the Pine Palace on March 31, 1877.<ref name="Pine Palace Info"/>

=== Establishment of Nakatsu Daijingu and Nakatsu Shrine ===
[[File:Nakatsu Daijingu ac (2).jpg|thumb|Torii of Nakatsu Shrines]]

Nakatsu Daijingu was established in 1881 (Meiji 14) as the Buzen Shrine Association, enshrining spirits from {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Grand Shrine|qq=}}. Initially, it served as a center for pilgrims from the Buzen region, distributing {{ill|Ise talismans|ja|神宮大麻|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise talismans|qq=}} and calendars.<ref name="Nakatsu Daijingu About"/> It underwent several name changes before being renamed Nakatsu Daijingu in 1946.

Nakatsu Shrine was established in 1883 (Meiji 16) on the former site of the Pine Palace. It consolidated deities from six local shrines, including Rokusho Shrine, Maruyama Shrine, and Hachiman Ōe Shrine.<ref name="Nakatsu Shrine About"/>

== Grounds ==
[[File:Nakatsu Castle Park ac (2).jpg|thumb|160px|“Nakatsu Corps Memorial”]]

The grounds feature several notable monuments:<ref name="Grounds Overview">[http://nakatsudaijinguu.jp/keidai.html Grounds Overview] Nakatsu Daijingu</ref>
* “Nakatsu Corps Memorial” - Dedicated to the Nakatsu Corps, which rose during the Satsuma Rebellion.
