* {{ill|Matsuo Bashō|en|Matsuo Bashō|qid=Q5676|lt=Matsuo Bashō|1=Matsuo Bashō}} Haiku Monument<ref name="Grounds Overview"/>
* Kii Shrine - Enshrines {{ill|Kii Tadamune|ja|城井鎮房|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kii Tadamune|1=Utsunomiya Shigefusa|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11425978}}, a lord assassinated at Nakatsu Castle by {{ill|Kuroda Nagamasa|en|Kuroda Nagamasa|qid=Q950496|lt=Kuroda Nagamasa|1=Kuroda Nagamasa}}.<ref name="Grounds Overview"/>
* Senjō Shrine - Dedicated to 45 retainers of Kii Tadamune.<ref name="Grounds Overview"/>
* Kotohira Shrine - Dedicated to the deity of maritime safety.<ref name="Grounds Overview"/>

== Festivals ==
{{main|{{ill|Nakatsu Gion Festival|ja|中津祇園|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakatsu Gion Festival|qq=}}}}
Nakatsu Gion, held annually in late July, features {{ill|Mikoshi|en|Mikoshi|qid=Q979940|lt=Mikoshi|1=Mikoshi}} and {{ill|Matsuri float|en|Matsuri float|qid=Q11470974|lt=Yamahoko|1=Matsuri float}} processions. The festival is centered on Yasaka Shrine (a subsidiary of {{ill|Yamami Shrine|ja|闇無濱神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamami Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 闇無浜神社|1=Kuranashihama Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q130214370}}) and Nakatsu Shrine, collectively known as Nakatsu Gion. Records trace its origins to 1430 (Eikyō 2). Nakatsu Gion is considered one of the “Three Great Festivals of Buzen” and “Three Major Gion Festivals of Ōita Prefecture.”<ref name="Nakatsu Gion History">[https://nakatsu-gion.com/rekishi/ About Nakatsu Gion] Nakatsu Gion</ref> It was designated a {{ill|Ōita Prefecture Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|大分県選択無形民俗文化財|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōita Prefecture Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in 1962 (Shōwa 37) and upgraded to a Prefectural Intangible Folk Cultural Property in 2004.<ref name="#1">[https://www.city-nakatsu.jp/doc/2011100115127/ Prefectural Cultural Properties] Nakatsu City</ref>

